'''Absolution''', ''<code>[[noun (part of speech)|noun]]</code>'' [F. ''absolution'', L. ''absolutio'', fr. ''absolvere'' to [[absolve]]. See [[Absolve]].]

<ol>
<li>An [[absolving]], or setting free from guilt, sin, or penalty; [[forgiven]]ess]] of an offense.

<code>Government ... granting ''absolution'' to the nation.</code> ''[[Froude (source)|Froude]].''

<li> ''(Civil Law)'' An [[acquittal]], or sentence of a judge [[declaring]] and accused person [[innocent]]. [Obs.]

<li> ''([[R. C. Ch (subject)|R. C. Ch]]).'' The exercise of [[priestly]] jurisdiction in the [[sacrament]] of [[penance]], by which Catholics believe the sins of the [[truly]] [[penitent]] are forgiven.

'''''Note:''''' In the English and other [[Protestant]] churches, this act regarded as simply [[declaratory]], not as [[imparting]] forgiveness.

<li> ''([[Eccl (subject)|Eccl]]).'' An absolving from ecclesiastical [[penalties]], -- for example, [[excommunication]]. ''[[P. Cyc (source)|P. Cyc]].''

<li> The form of words by which a penitent is [[absolved]]. ''[[Shipley (source)|Shipley]].''

<li> Delivery, in speech. [Obs.] ''[[B. Jonson (source)|B. Jonson]].''

'''Absolution day''' ''([[R. C. Ch (subject)|R. C. Ch]]).'', [[Tuesday]] before [[Easter]].
</ol>